enzyme","Increases testosterone metabolism","Competitive antagonism at androgen receptors","Suppresses luteinising hormone release","Blocks testosterone synthesis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of antiandrogens is through \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompetitive antagonism at androgen receptors\u003C/strong\u003E. These drugs bind to androgen receptors without activating them, preventing testosterone and dihydrotestosterone from exerting their effects on target tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of the 5-alpha reductase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of finasteride and dutasteride, which prevent conversion of testosterone to dihydrotestosterone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases testosterone metabolism\u003C/strong\u003E - antiandrogens do not affect the metabolic breakdown of androgens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppresses luteinising hormone release\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of gonadotrophin-releasing hormone analogues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks testosterone synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of drugs like ketoconazole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntiandrogens are used to treat various conditions including prostate cancer, hirsutism, and androgenic alopecia. Common examples include flutamide, bicalutamide, and spironolactone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Antiandrogens work by competitively binding to androgen receptors without activating them, preventing the action of testosterone and dihydrotestosterone.","Antiandrogens are used clinically to treat conditions driven by excess androgens, including prostate cancer and hirsutism.","Common antiandrogens include flutamide, bicalutamide, and spironolactone."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61729"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16624"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61729"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T14:33:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T14:35:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9315"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76225"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"d